    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d079ec3f_34cbb636",
        "filename": "go/boltutil/store.go",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 63,
      "author": {
        "id": 5120
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-11-23T02:10:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m not 100% sure this will work, but IMO it will be nicer to have something like:\ntype DecoderFactory interface {\n  NewDecoder() Decoder\n}\ntype Decoder interface {\n  // Process decodes the byte slice and includes it in AsRecords().\n  // Caller must ensure b does not change until after AsRecords() returns.\n  Process(b []byte) err\n  // AsRecords returns all decoded Records provided to Process, or\n  // any error encountered.\n  AsRecords() ([]Record, error)\n}\n\nAlso, add Encode method to Record.\n\nThen we would replace return value of List and Read and argument of WriteFn with Decoder. This would allow me to use MyTypeDecoder, where I can add a convenience method:\nAsMyType() ([]MyType, error)\n\nThis is based on the public methods of TaskDecoder: https://skia.googlesource.com/buildbot/+/dc5e7cb1cbcdb4d4900e96236cce66d2f6985594/task_scheduler/go/db/task.go#461\nI found that decoding byte slices takes a significant amount of time, and assuming you\u0027re reading more than a couple records, decoding in parallel makes things much faster. (TaskDecoder gives the results in arbitrary order because I didn\u0027t need them to be stable, but it shouldn\u0027t be too hard to change it to be stable.)",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 61,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 63,
        "endChar": 20
      },
      "revId": "934d452274e35e40ffc77e3ba16e9b5616afbc99",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "50d33c96_6a1ff723",
        "filename": "go/boltutil/store.go",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 63,
      "author": {
        "id": 5620
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-11-23T19:33:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I favor the (misnamed) LRUCodec interface, because it handles exactly one serialization format of a type, where the type doesn\u0027t need to know how it is being (de)serialized. \nIt also keeps the encode/decode functions for a type close together. It also let\u0027s you write generic encoders, i.e. JSONCodec(\u0026MyType{}) produces a JSON codec for any type.\n(see: https://github.com/google/skia-buildbot/blob/master/go/util/caching.go#L119).\n\nAgreed that the encoding/decoding should be done in parallel, but it should actually be done in the read/write functions of the Store type. The client of the type should not be concerned about about making it parallel, but only how to get from bytes to instance and vice versa.\n\nI see that TaskScheduler doesn\u0027t store a serialized task directly in BoltDB directly\nbut prefixes it with a version and a timestamp (see task_scheduler/go/db/local_db/local_db.go).\n\nLet\u0027s adapt it accommodate TaskScheduler when we have used it in a few other places. \nThen we\u0027ll know if it\u0027s a good fit for TaskScheduler and we can change the API accordingly.",
      "parentUuid": "d079ec3f_34cbb636",
      "revId": "934d452274e35e40ffc77e3ba16e9b5616afbc99",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
