    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d079ec3f_d147e41c",
        "filename": "go/boltutil/store.go",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 231,
      "author": {
        "id": 5120
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-11-23T02:10:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It\u0027s hard for me to imagine a use for this that won\u0027t behave in unexpected ways.\n\nIf you want to iterate over all records in the DB, use bolt.Bucket.ForEach (or if you\u0027re worried about a long-lived read Tx, provide an API similar to ForEach that under-the-covers uses something like below).\n\nIf you want to implement paging, integer offsets tend not to work well, because adding new records causes the same record to appear on multiple pages, while deleting records causes records to be skipped. Instead, your API should look like:\nList(lastKey string, count int)\nIf lastKey is \"\", then start at the first record. Otherwise, start at the first record after lastKey. Read count records or until reaching the end of the bucket.\n\nYou can then do something like:\nr, _ \u003d List(\"\", 10)\nr, _ \u003d List(r[len(r)-1].Key(), 10)\nr, _ \u003d List(r[len(r)-1].Key(), 10)\n\nIf you also need to iterate backwards, it\u0027s easy enough to add a \"direction\" parameter:\nr, _ \u003d List(BEFORE, r[0].Key(), 10)\nr, _ \u003d List(AFTER, r[len(r)-1].Key(), 10)",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 230,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 231,
        "endChar": 38
      },
      "revId": "934d452274e35e40ffc77e3ba16e9b5616afbc99",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4df48341_421854ed",
        "filename": "go/boltutil/store.go",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 231,
      "author": {
        "id": 5620
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-11-23T19:33:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The approach with lastKey doesn\u0027t really solve the problem IMO. If new keys are inserted before lastKey it will miss them as well. \n\nI added a TODO to revisit this base on how it is used and included a warning into the documentation that results might be inconsistent between calls. \n\nThe only use case I see for this right now is for datasets where I am primarily interested in the first \u0027size\u0027 records and in testing to enumerate everything that is in my database right now.",
      "parentUuid": "d079ec3f_d147e41c",
      "revId": "934d452274e35e40ffc77e3ba16e9b5616afbc99",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4df48341_487ab3db",
        "filename": "go/boltutil/store.go",
        "patchSetId": 13
      },
      "lineNbr": 231,
      "author": {
        "id": 5120
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-11-23T20:54:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yes, neither approach to paging will show results that are logically before the current page, but that\u0027s a feature, not a bug.\n\nThe indexed approach can result in an item appearing at the end of one page, and then when I go to the next page, the same item appears at the beginning of the page due to a new item being inserted. The lastKey approach does not have that problem.\n\nIt sounds like you want the ForEach API, which can exit early after reading the first \u0027size\u0027 records.",
      "parentUuid": "4df48341_421854ed",
      "revId": "934d452274e35e40ffc77e3ba16e9b5616afbc99",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
